[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** Same chapter pattern as 11.4, 11.5, 11.6, and 11.7 with recipe-distinct mental-health-PHI-of-most-sensitive-variety, multi-year-mental-health-record-accumulation, mandatory-reporting-disclosure-handling, and 42 CFR Part 2 amplification extensions. The recipe correctly elevates the longitudinal store accumulating mental-health PHI and the support-decision-record-journal as the durable answer-record-equivalent for support events and the sensitive-disclosure store as a separately-keyed and access-restricted surface. Despite this elevation, the architecture pattern, the diagram, and the pseudocode treat the longitudinal-store, decision-record-journal, sensitive-disclosure store, crisis-event-record, and tool-call-ledger writes as embedding rather than referencing the per-conversation and per-event content. Recipe-acute and recipe-distinct because:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   1. **The longitudinal store is recipe-acute as the bot's load-bearing-mental-health-record artifact accumulating multi-year PHI of the most sensitive variety.** The longitudinal store accumulates conversation history, sensitive-disclosure flags, crisis-history flags, symptom-tracking baselines, mental-health diagnoses, psychiatric medications, safety-plan references, and patient preferences over months and years. State mental-health-record retention obligations apply alongside HIPAA's six-year minimum (per-state mental-health-record retention rules vary; many states have specifically enhanced retention rules for mental-health records that exceed general medical-record rules). 42 CFR Part 2 applies for substance-use treatment records with specific retention and disclosure rules. FDA SaMD post-market obligations may extend retention further. The architecture should specify the per-state and per-pediatric and per-FDA-SaMD and per-42-CFR-Part-2 retention floor reconciliation and the per-record-class retention regime distinct from the audit-archive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   2. **The decision_record's decision_payload and citations are clinically-significant elements with their own retention and access-control profiles.** The decision_payload contains the patient's recommendation context including potentially-sensitive disclosures (suicidality, self-harm history, substance-use, trauma, intimate-partner violence, mandatory-reporting-relevant content); the citations contain the therapeutic-content-element, psychoeducation, and safety-plan references that ground the response; some elements are part of the formal mental-health record at some institutions; some are part of the audit-pipeline; each element has its own retention and access-control profile.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   3. **Mandatory-reporting-relevant disclosures are recipe-distinct additionally-sensitive content that should never be embedded inline in the support-decision-record-journal without explicit access-control gate.** Patients in mental-health support relationships disclose: child abuse (if pediatric or caregiver disclosure), elder abuse (if geriatric or caregiver disclosure), intimate-partner violence, severe mental-health crisis, substance-use issues. Each is statutorily protected with additional layers of access control, special handling, and per-jurisdiction reporting workflows. The architecture should specify the per-disclosure-class handling (sensitive disclosures route to the separately-governed sensitive-disclosure surface with restricted access; the support-decision-record-journal should not embed mandatory-reporting-relevant disclosures inline).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   4. **The crisis-event record is recipe-distinct life-safety-acute content.** The crisis-event record contains the patient's crisis-screen results across dimensions (passive_ideation, active_ideation, plan, means, intent, timeline, self_harm_thoughts, self_harm_behaviors, homicidal_ideation, psychotic_symptoms, overdose_risk), the screening result, the active-classifier-version, the active-consent-version. The architecture has correctly elevated this to a separately-keyed surface (good); the architecture should specify the working-store discipline (recent crisis-event records in DynamoDB hot path; archive to S3 with separately-keyed encryption for long-term) explicitly, with retention bounded by the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, state-specific mental-health-record retention rules, FDA SaMD post-market obligations, and litigation-hold obligations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   5. **The conversation log accumulating across years is dense mental-health PHI plus may include crisis disclosures.** The recipe's prose elevates the conversation history retention as multi-year. The architecture should specify the per-record-class retention reconciliation (audit-archive vs support-decision-record-journal vs longitudinal-store vs conversation-log vs sensitive-disclosure-archive vs crisis-event-archive vs version-stamp-registry retention may differ; some institutions treat the conversation log as part of the mental-health record while others treat it as an audit-pipeline artifact; some state mental-health-record laws specifically address patient-communication retention; some patient consents specifically address conversation-log retention).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   6. **The per-record-class access-control surface is not specified.** The audit pipeline's access-control surface is the audit-and-compliance team plus the privacy officer. The longitudinal-store's access-control surface is the patient's care team (with consent) plus the patient (through the institution's patient-record-access pathway per HIPAA). The support-decision-record-journal's access-control surface is the behavioral-health clinical leadership plus the operations team plus the compliance team plus the audit-and-compliance team plus the data-science team for outcome-correlation plus the patient (through the institution's patient-record-access pathway). The sensitive-disclosure-store's access-control surface is restricted to a smaller set of licensed clinicians and compliance personnel. The crisis-event-record's access-control surface is restricted to licensed clinicians plus compliance plus operations. Each record class has different access-control needs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   7. **The patient's right to access their longitudinal record per HIPAA and (per state and contract) right to request deletion is not architecturally elevated.** The architecture should specify the patient-right-of-access workflow (the patient can review their longitudinal store contents per HIPAA), the state-and-contract-permitted deletion workflow (some states and some institutional contracts permit patient-initiated deletion of mental-health records with specific exceptions), and the deletion-vs-retention-conflict resolution (FDA SaMD post-market obligations, certain state mental-health-record laws, and 42 CFR Part 2 may prohibit deletion of certain record classes; mandatory-reporting-relevant disclosures may have separate retention obligations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   8. **The 42 CFR Part 2 alignment for substance-use treatment records is recipe-distinct.** The recipe correctly elevates 42 CFR Part 2 in multiple places. The architecture should specify the per-record-class flagging when 42 CFR Part 2 applies, the separate consent-and-disclosure workflow for substance-use treatment records, and the cross-system reconciliation when 42 CFR Part 2 records are referenced in non-Part-2 records.
